   <conbody>
      <div class="- topic/div ">
         <hazardstatement id="HighOutputVoltageBeforeChangingToEq-FEC789C7"
                          type="notice"
                          class="+ topic/note hazard-d/hazardstatement ">
            <messagepanel class="+ topic/ul hazard-d/messagepanel ">
               <typeofhazard class="+ topic/li hazard-d/typeofhazard ">High output voltage AND REDUCED CURRENT</typeofhazard>
               <howtoavoid class="+ topic/li hazard-d/howtoavoid ">Never enable equalization charge mode with a load connected
to the DC output.</howtoavoid>
               <howtoavoid platform="Modular-AC" class="+ topic/li hazard-d/howtoavoid ">Never enable equalization charge
mode with the inverter modules in operation.</howtoavoid>
            </messagepanel>
         </hazardstatement>
         <p class="- topic/p ">Equalization charge mode uses
a high output voltage to overcharge the battery. Equalization charge
is mainly used to condition the battery during its commissioning.</p>
         <p conref="M_Boost_Charge_CPT_0000735394.dita#BoostCharge-EF574918/ThisModeIsATemporaryModeAndIsOnlyUs-01467D53"
            class="- topic/p ">This mode is a temporary mode and is only used for a short period
of time.</p>
         <note platform="Modular-AC" type="important" class="- topic/note ">Never have
the inverter modules in operation during equalization charge. Make
sure the manual bypass switch is turned to the bypass output position,
see <xref href="M_How_to_Change_to_Manual_Bypass_from_Static_Switch_Operation_TSK_0001086583.dita"
                  scope="local"
                  type="task"
                  class="- topic/xref "/>.</note>
         <note class="- topic/note ">Equalization charge can only be activated manually.</note>
         <note id="ItIsPossibleToInhibitEqualizingChar-FECA9B56" class="- topic/note ">It is possible
to inhibit equalization charge. If equalization charge is inhibited,
the rectifier modules cannot manually change to equalization charge.
Equalization charge can be inhibited permanently (not available for
the system) or by an external signal.</note>
